# Next.js 16 App Router Patterns

## Context
- Next.js 16 with App Router
- Server Components by default
- Client Components when needed

## Requirements

### Route Parameters (CRITICAL)
- Route params are async Promises - MUST await them
- Type as `params: Promise<{ id: string }>`
- Await before use: `const { id } = await params`

### Server vs Client Components

**Default to Server Components**:
```typescript
export default async function Page() {
  const data = await fetchData();
  return <Component data={data} />;
}
```

**Use 'use client' when needed**:
- useState, useEffect, useReducer
- Event handlers (onClick, onChange)
- Browser APIs

### Page Patterns

```typescript
// app/items/[id]/page.tsx
interface PageProps {
  params: Promise<{ id: string }>;
}

export default async function ItemPage({ params }: PageProps) {
  const { id } = await params;
  const item = await fetchItem(id);
  
  if (!item) notFound();
  return <ItemDetail item={item} />;
}
```

## Examples

<example>
✅ Correct dynamic route:
```typescript
export default async function Page({
  params,
}: {
  params: Promise<{ slug: string }>;
}) {
  const { slug } = await params;
  return <div>{slug}</div>;
}
```
</example>

<example type="invalid">
❌ Missing await (will error):
```typescript
export default function Page({
  params,
}: {
  params: { slug: string };
}) {
  const { slug } = params; // ERROR
  return <div>{slug}</div>;
}
```
</example>

<critical>
- NEVER forget to await params in Next.js 16
- ALWAYS type params as Promise
</critical>
